<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">Adult habitus.</emphasis>
Triocellate. General colour greenish in the field, but becoming pale brown in ethanol. The head is also black in the field, but changes to brown in ethanol. Head with rounded pale yellow spot between compound eye and lateral ocellus, frons dark brown from epicranial suture to clypeus and with broad pale areas along lateral margins adjacent to antennal bases. Compound eyes dark greyish, ocelli greyish, anterior ocellus paler with dark black margins; antennae and palpi pale. The pronotum disc is completely brown, bearing symmetrical rugosities, margin dark brown (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7639633" captionText="Figure 1. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. male holotype. A head and pronotum dorsal view; B terminalia dorsal view; C terminalia ventral view; D terminalia lateral view; E epiproct. Scale bar 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/669422" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">1</figureCitation>
A); mesonotae and metanotae brown with U-shaped marking, margin dark. Wings hyaline, forewing Rs branched, the anal field of hind-wing small and folded with three veins, legs pale. Abdominal terga 1-7 dorsally with brown median stripe of trapezoidal spots and tergum 8 with small rounded spot anteromedially, lateral dark patches also present on segments 1-4 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7639637" captionText="Figure 2. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. A male holotype, abdomen dorsal view; B female paratype, abdomen dorsal view. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/669419" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">2</figureCitation>
A). Cerci pale with long setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" type="male">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">Male</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">
Body length 8.5-9.5 mm (n = 3); forewing length 7.0-7.5 mm, hind-wing length 6.2-6.8 mm. Tergum 9 sclerotised, posteriorly strongly sclerotised bearing long brown hairs, dorsally without any ridge and stripe. Tergum 10 divided medially; the medial portion enlarged, forming a shield-like structure with a dark brown basal anchor (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7639633" captionText="Figure 1. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. male holotype. A head and pronotum dorsal view; B terminalia dorsal view; C terminalia ventral view; D terminalia lateral view; E epiproct. Scale bar 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/669422" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">1</figureCitation>
B-D). Epiproct long and spoon-shaped, parallel-sided for most of its length, but constricted medially, broad from the basal portion, dorsolaterally sclerotised, apically rounded and apex forming spoon-bowl shape in dorsal view (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7639633" captionText="Figure 1. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. male holotype. A head and pronotum dorsal view; B terminalia dorsal view; C terminalia ventral view; D terminalia lateral view; E epiproct. Scale bar 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/669422" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F7639641" captionText="Figure 3. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. male holotype. A epiproct dorsal view; B epiproct lateral view. Scale bar 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/631122" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">3</figureCitation>
A); in lateral aspect, the epiproct is thin and parallel for its most part, apically wide and slightly curved at the apex (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7639633" captionText="Figure 1. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. male holotype. A head and pronotum dorsal view; B terminalia dorsal view; C terminalia ventral view; D terminalia lateral view; E epiproct. Scale bar 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/669422" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F7639641" captionText="Figure 3. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. male holotype. A epiproct dorsal view; B epiproct lateral view. Scale bar 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/631122" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">3</figureCitation>
B). Aedeagus is completely membranous, triangular in shape. The dorsal and dorsolateral lobes are slightly rounded in shape, basal portion bulbous. The posterior portion of the aedeagus bears a pair of finger-like apical lobes, each covered with numerous long hairs (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F7639645" captionText="Figure 4. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. male paratype. A aedeagus dorsal view; B aedeagus ventral view. Scale bar 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/631123" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" type="female">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">Female</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">
Body length 9.5-10 mm (n = 3); forewing length 8.0-8.5 mm, hind-wing length 7.0-7.5 mm. Habitus is generally similar to the male. Head and pronotum are darker than the males. Abdominal tergum 1-4 dorsally with median stripe of brown trapezoidal spots and terga 5-7 with median stripe of oval shape (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7639637" captionText="Figure 2. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. A male holotype, abdomen dorsal view; B female paratype, abdomen dorsal view. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/669419" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">2</figureCitation>
B). Sternum 8 bears a triangular sclerotised subgenital plate, reaching near to the posterior margin of sternum 9; covered with tiny hairs. Posterior margin of the subgenital plate is with a large triangular posteromedial notch (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F7639653" captionText="Figure 5. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. female paratype. A head and pronotum; B terminalia ventral view. Scale bar 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/631124" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">5</figureCitation>
A-B).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" type="egg">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">Egg</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">Unknown</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" type="nymph">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">Nymph</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">
Habitus (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F7639649" captionText="Figure 6. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. nymph. A dorsal view; B ventral view. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/669434" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">6</figureCitation>
A-B). Body length 7.0-7.5 mm (n = 2). General body colour brown with an obscure pattern of darker brown. Head primarily brown, ocellar area and frons bear a rectangular darker pigmentation, except for pale areas near antennal bases and along anterior margin of frons covering clypeus; dark area of head consists of several oval spots, the two pale spots on the lateral sides of median ocellus and two spots on frons above median ocellus, occiput mostly pale. Compound eyes dark, ocelli greyish, anterior ocellus paler with dark black margin. Pronotum disc dark brown with darker submarginal bands along posterior and anterior margins; the lateral margins brown, disc without an obvious pattern (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7639657" captionText="Figure 7. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. nymph. A head and pronotum; B thorax and wing-pads; C terminalia dorsal view; D cerci dorsal view. Scale bar 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/631126" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">7</figureCitation>
A). The pronotal setal fringes are well-developed, with two-thirds of anterior margin and complete along posterior margin. Mesonotae and metanotae with distinct U-shaped marking, basal bristle patch of mixed length setae; wing pad developed and margins with few bristles (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7639657" captionText="Figure 7. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. nymph. A head and pronotum; B thorax and wing-pads; C terminalia dorsal view; D cerci dorsal view. Scale bar 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/631126" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">7</figureCitation>
B). The entire thoracic segments and abdomen are covered with pale brown hairs. Abdominal segments 7-9 covered with small and long bristles; lateral bristle is typical. Cerci pale brown (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7639657" captionText="Figure 7. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. nymph. A head and pronotum; B thorax and wing-pads; C terminalia dorsal view; D cerci dorsal view. Scale bar 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/631126" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">7</figureCitation>
C). Cersal bristles are well-developed, apical segmented whorls; basal are segmented with shorter bristles, the apical segment with at least one or two dorsal bristles equal in length or slightly longer than the following segment (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7639657" captionText="Figure 7. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. nymph. A head and pronotum; B thorax and wing-pads; C terminalia dorsal view; D cerci dorsal view. Scale bar 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/631126" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">7</figureCitation>
D). Leg pale, femora and tibia covered with sparse dorsal silky setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">This new species is characterised by the dark pigmentation of the head, pronotum and the shape of epiproct. Tergum 9 is sclerotised without any ridge and stripe. Epiproct is long and spoon-shaped, apically rounded in dorsal view; in lateral aspect, the epiproct is thin and parallel for its most part, apically wide and slightly curved at the apex.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">Etymology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">
The name of the new species refers to the shape of the epiproct that is spoon-shaped. The Latin &quot; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rehman, Huo &amp; Du" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Sweltsa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sweltsa ligula" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ligula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">Sweltsa ligula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot; means spoon shape.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">China (Guizhou Province).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">
The new species is very similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zhiltzova &amp; Levanidova" authorityYear="1978" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Sweltsa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sweltsa colorata" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="colorata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">Sweltsa colorata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Zhiltzova &amp; Levanidova, 1978 in 
<bibRefCitation author="Teslenko, V. A." journalOrPublisher="University of Illinois Press, Urbana and Chicago, Illinois" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" pagination=": 382 pp" refId="B7639583" refString="Teslenko, V. A., Zhiltzova, L. A., 2009. Key to the stoneflies (Insecta, Plecoptera) of Russia and adjacent countries. Imagines and nymphs. Dalnauka Vladivostok. In: Dalnauka Vladivostok.: 382 pp" title="Key to the stoneflies (Insecta, Plecoptera) of Russia and adjacent countries. Imagines and nymphs. Dalnauka Vladivostok" volumeTitle="Dalnauka Vladivostok." year="2009">Teslenko and Zhiltzova (2009)</bibRefCitation>
. The new species can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. colorata" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" rank="species" species="colorata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">S. colorata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the head, pronotum pigmentation and the shape of the epiproct. The head and pronotum disc of the new species are highly sclerotised and darker than 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. colorata" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" rank="species" species="colorata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">S. colorata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7639633" captionText="Figure 1. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. male holotype. A head and pronotum dorsal view; B terminalia dorsal view; C terminalia ventral view; D terminalia lateral view; E epiproct. Scale bar 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/669422" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">1</figureCitation>
A). The abdominal tergum stripe of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. colorata" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" rank="species" species="colorata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">S. colorata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to the new species. The epiproct of the new species is broad with a spoon-bowl-shaped apex in dorsal view (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F7639641" captionText="Figure 3. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. male holotype. A epiproct dorsal view; B epiproct lateral view. Scale bar 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/631122" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">3</figureCitation>
A-B), while the epiproct of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. colorata" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" rank="species" species="colorata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">S. colorata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a pointed apex and is more slender than the new species (see figs. 505 and 506 in 
<bibRefCitation author="Teslenko, V. A." journalOrPublisher="University of Illinois Press, Urbana and Chicago, Illinois" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" pagination=": 382 pp" refId="B7639583" refString="Teslenko, V. A., Zhiltzova, L. A., 2009. Key to the stoneflies (Insecta, Plecoptera) of Russia and adjacent countries. Imagines and nymphs. Dalnauka Vladivostok. In: Dalnauka Vladivostok.: 382 pp" title="Key to the stoneflies (Insecta, Plecoptera) of Russia and adjacent countries. Imagines and nymphs. Dalnauka Vladivostok" volumeTitle="Dalnauka Vladivostok." year="2009">Teslenko and Zhiltzova 2009</bibRefCitation>
). In the lateral aspect, the epiproct of the new species is slender and parallel for its most part, apically wide and slightly curved, which easily distinguished the new species. The female of the new species is different from the female of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. colorata" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" rank="species" species="colorata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">S. colorata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The female subgenital plate of the new species posteriorly has a medial notch, while the female of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. colorata" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433" rank="species" species="colorata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">S. colorata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is without any prominent notch, characteristics which easily differentiate these two females. The nymph lives on the surface of the stream near the waterfall (stream width is 2-3 m and the water depth is no more than 30 cm). The adults often emerged under the wide rocks (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F7639661" captionText="Figure 8. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. type locality. A, B adults on the rock; C, D habitat; E distributional map, with type locality marked in red." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/631127" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">8</figureCitation>
A-B) and stayed on the surrounding trees, especially in bamboo (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F7639661" captionText="Figure 8. Sweltsa ligula Rehman, Huo &amp; Du sp. n. type locality. A, B adults on the rock; C, D habitat; E distributional map, with type locality marked in red." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e80433.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/631127" pageId="0" pageNumber="80433">8</figureCitation>
C-D).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
